Madrid \u201cTransparente\u201d, New York Film Festival, US\n* 2005 Sol De Plata, Metro de Madrid \u201cTransparente\u201d, El Sol 2005 (San Sebasti\u00e1n), Spain\n* 2005 Sol De Bronce, Cowboy \u201cDodot Etapas\u201d, El Sol 2005 (San Sebasti\u00e1n), Spain\n* 2005 Best Advert, Coca-Cola \u201cDel Pita\u201d, Premios \u201cEl Chupete\u201d, Spain\n* 2005 Best Integrated Marketing Program, Coca-Cola \u201cDel Pita\u201d, Marketing Excellence Awards (TCCC), UK\n* 2005 Gold, Coca-Cola \u201cDel Pita\u201d, \u201cPremios A.M.P.E. 2005, Spain\n* 2005 Bronze, Coca-Cola \u201cDel Pita\u201d, New York Film Festival, US\n* 2004 Gold, Coca-Cola \u201cDel Pita\u201d, Premios A.P.P.E. (Asociaci\u00f3n de Productoras Publicitarias Espa\u00f1olas), Spain\n* 2004 Finalist, Coca-Cola \u201cMusical\u201d, Premios El Sol B, Spain\n* 2004 Finalist, Coca-Cola \u201cMusical\u201d, Cannes Lions, France [http://www.canneslions.com]\n* 2004 Finalist, Coca-Cola \u201cMusical\u201d, London International Awards,UK<ref>http://2008.liaawards.com/2004/finalists/finalists/tv/tv05.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810162113/http://2008.liaawards.com/2004/finalists/finalists/tv/tv05.html |date=2011-08-10 }} Title: '2004 Finalists: TELEVISION/CINEMA', Author: London International Awards, \"Entrant: McCann-Erickson, Madrid, Coca-Cola - Musical, Agency: McCann-Erickson, Madrid\", Section: 'Archive Winners and Finalists', Publisher: London International Awards - Official Site, 'Celebrating the power of ideas', Retrieved: 4 April 2011</ref>[http://www.liaawards.com]\n* 2003 Finalist, Coca-Cola \u201cMusical\u201d, Premios Zapping, Spain\n* 2003 Best Advert, Coca-Cola \u201cMusical\u201d, [[TP de Oro]], Spain\n\n==Advertising music==\n\n===International brands===\n\nAudi, [[Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria]], B.M.W., Bongrain SA, Carlsberg, [[Carrefour]], Coca-Cola, Ford, [[Girlguiding UK]], [[I.B.M.]], [[IKEA]], Illva Saronno, [[Movistar]], Nestl\u00e9, Orange, Pepsi, Peugeot, Procter & Gamble, Renault, Sammontana, Santander, Sony PlayStation, [[Ssang Yong]], [[Sunny Delight Beverages Co.|Sunny Delight]], Telef\u00f3nica, Turismo Espa\u00f1a, Turismo Madrid [http://www.turismomadrid.es], [[Visa Inc.|Visa]]\n\n===Spanish brands===\n\nAsociaci\u00f3n Nacional para el desarrollo de la Salud en la Mujer,[http://www.adesam.org] Adif, Aena,[http://www.aena.es] [[Orange Espa\u00f1a|Amena]], [[Antena Tres]], [[Aviva]], [[Barcel\u00f3]], Caballero,[http://www.caballero.es] Caja Madrid, [[Canal Plus]], [[Castilla La Mancha]], Cerveza Mixta, [[Comit\u00e9 Ol\u00edmpico Espa\u00f1ol]], [[Comunidad de Madrid]], [[Cuatro (channel)|Cuatro]], [[El Corte Ingl\u00e9s]], [[Endesa (Spain)|Endesa]], [[Ferrovial]], [[:es:Colchones Flex|Flex]],[http://www.flex.es] [[:es:Fuerzas Armadas de Espa\u00f1a|Fuerzas Armadas de Espa\u00f1a]], Fundaci\u00f3n Irene Meg\u00edas,[http://www.contralameningitis.org] Hipotecas.Com,[http://www.hipotecas.com] [[Jazztel]], [[:es:Kalise|Kalise]], Larios [https://web.archive.org/web/20110501093117/http://www.lariosdrygin.com/] [[laSexta]], [[:es:Metro Madrid|Metro Madrid]], [[:es:Ministerio de Trabajo e Inmigraci\u00f3n de Espa\u00f1a|Ministerio de Trabajo e Inmigraci\u00f3n de Espa\u00f1a]], Multi\u00d3pticas,[http://www.multiopticas.com] Once,[http://www.once.es] M\u00fatua Madrile\u00f1a, Orlando,[http://www.heinz.es] P\u00e1ginas Amarillas,[http://www.paginas-amarillas.es] [[Celta de Vigo|Real Club Celta de Vigo]],[https://web.archive.org/web/20121026162844/http://www.celtavigo.net/] [[RTVE]], [[:es:Seguros Ocaso|Santa Luc\u00eda]],[http://www.santalucia.es] [[Telecinco]], [[Televisi\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola]], Tesoro P\u00fablico [https://web.archive.org/web/20110319085034/http://www.tesoro.es/sp/index.asp]\n\n==Film music==\n\n===Film features===\nUpdated list at [https://www.imdb.com/filmosearch/?explore=title_type&role=nm2833257&ref_=filmo_vw_adv&mode=advanced&page=1&sort=release_date,desc IMDB]\n\n* 2018 \"Ser\u00e1s hombre\", Director: Isabel de Ocampo\n*2017 \"Toc Toc\", Director: Vicente Villanueva, Lazona\n*2011 \"Evelyn\", Director: Isabel de Ocampo, La Voz Que Yo Amo.\n* 2011 \u201cLooking For Eimish\u201d (Buscando an Eimish), Director: Ana Rodriguez, Jana Films.\n* 2011 \u201cImp\u00e1vido\u201d, Director: Carlos Ther\u00f3n, Enigma Films.\n* 2010 \u201cThe Vampire In The Hole\u201d, Director: Sonia Escolano & Sadrac Gonz\u00e1lez, LaSoga/Lukantum.\n* 2006 \u201cLa M\u00e1quina De Bailar\u201d, Director: [[:es:\u00d3scar Aibar|\u00d3scar de Aibar]], [[:es:Amiguetes Entertainment|Amiguetes Entertainment]]/Ensue\u00f1o Films/Chapuzas Audiovisuales.\n\n===Film shorts (outdated)===\n\n* 2010 \"The Recipient\", Director: Javier Berm\u00fadez, Fanatico Films.\n* 2009 \u201cTerapia\u201d, Director: Nuria Verde (Premios Goya Award Nominee for Best Fictional Short Film 2010).\n* 2009 \"Sea Bed\", Director: Laura M. Campos, Antipop Films.\n* 2008 \u201cMadrid 2016\u201d, Comunidad de Madrid.\n* 2008 \u201c\u00a1Al Cielo Con Ella!\u201d, Director: Nicol\u00e1s Pacheco, La Tapia Producciones/Secuencia Imagen y Comunicaci\u00f3n.\n* 2008 \u201cEstrella\u201d, Director: Bel\u00e9n Herrera de la Osa.\n* 2008 \u201cMiente\u201d, Producc\u00edones L\u00edqu\u00eddas, Director: Isabel de Ocampo, Mandil.\n* 2007 \u201cImp\u00e1vido\u201d, Mandr\u00edl, Starring Marta Torn\u00e9, Director: Carlos Ther\u00f3n, Producciones L\u00edquidas.\n* 2007 \"Never Ending\", Director: Laura M. Campos, Antipop Films.\n* 2005 \"Good Partners\" (Buenos compa\u00f1eros), Director: Miguel de Priego.\n* 2005 \u201cMrs Eriksson In Spain\" (La se\u00f1ora Eriksson en Espa\u00f1a) (Audio Mixing), Director: Carita Boronska, Tonetailor Productions.\n\n===Television / TV Shows===\n* 2011 \"H\u00e1ztelo Mirar\", TV series, Directors: V\u00edctor Mart\u00edn Le\u00f3n & David Velduque, Antena 3 Neox.\n* 2010 \"Desalmados\", TV series (online), Director: V\u00edctor Mart\u00edn Le\u00f3n, Antena 3.\n* 2009 \"18RDC (Ritmo De la Calle)\", Videomedia, TV series, Executive Producers: Cristina Castilla & Eva S\u00e1nchez, Antena 3.\n* 2003 \"Communicate\", TV campaign, R.T.V.E.\n\n==Recordings==\n\n===Albums===\n\n* 2011 Nieva \"Sed Del Mar\" (pending)\n* 2010 Ni\u00f1o Raro \u201cTreinta y Tres\u201d\n* 2009 Maydr\u00efm \u201cMakeyourselfagain\u201d\n* 2009 Lucas \"Palo Al Agua\" (EMI Espa\u00f1a)\n* 2008 Lonely Joe \u201cUn Toque De Lonely\u201d (Subterfuge Records)\n* 2006 Vanexxa \u201cSe Rompe O Se Raja\u201d (Subterfuge Records)\n* 2005 Lonely Joe \u201cSongs From The Low Side\u201d (Subterfuge Records)\n* 2004 Gladston Galliza \u201cTocca Essa Bola\u201d (Carlsberg)\n* 2003 Lonely Joe \u201cDark Ghost Of Shame\u201d (Junk Records)\n* 2001 Maydr\u00efm \"#Interactive\"\n* 2001 Jos\u00e9 Ortega \"La Rosa De Tu Piel\"\n\n===Singles===\n* 2011 Maydr\u00efm featuring Sara Montgomery-Campbell \"Never Ending\" (pending)\n* 2010 Maydr\u00efm featuring Sara Montgomery-Campbell \"Something\" (Pop Up M\u00fasica) [http://www.popupmusica.com]\n* 2008 Lucas \"\u00c9ste Coraz\u00f3n\" (EMI Espa\u00f1a)\n* 2006 Cycle \"Mechanical\"\n* 2005 Mar \"A Que No Me Callo\" (EMI Espa\u00f1a)\n* 2005 Maydr\u00efm featuring Monica Castell \"Killing Moon\" (Lunar Records)\n* 2005 Maydr\u00efm featuring Carita Boronska \"Shakespeare\u2019s Sister\" (El Diablo)\n* 2005 N\u00f3madas \"Creer En M\u00ed\" (Vale Music)\n\n===Remixes===\n\n* 2010 Compulsion \"Monsters\" (Maydr\u00efm Remix)\n* 2009 Munich 72 \"Cuando Dices Que No\" (Maydr\u00efm Remix)\n* 2006 In Strict Confidence \"Promised Land\" (Maydr\u00efm Remix) on In Strict Confidence \"The Serpent's Kiss\" (Minuswelt Musikfabrik)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/In-Strict-Confidence-The-Serpents-Kiss/release/820201|title=In Strict Confidence \u2013 The Serpent's Kiss|publisher=discogs.com|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n* 2000 Digital 21 \"Anymore\" (Maydr\u00efm Remix)\n* 1997 In The Dark \"Number One\" (Maydr\u00efm Remix)\n\n===Featured songs===\n\n* 2008 Luis Ramiro \"Estrella\" on \"Estrella\" film soundtrack\n* 2008 Marwan \u201cEl Pr\u00f3ximo Verano\" on Marwan \u201cTrapecista\u201d album\n* 2005 Maydr\u00efm featuring Monica Castell \"Killing Moon\" on Various Artistes \"Play the Game: Tributo a Echo and the Bunnymen\" (Lunar Records)\n* 2005 Maydr\u00efm featuring Carita Boronska \"Shakespeare's Sister\" on Various Artistes \"Una luz que nunca se apagar\u00e1: Tributo a The Smiths\" (El Diablo)\n\n===Session recordings===\n\n* 2011 Amaral \"Hacia Lo Salvaje\" album (Ant\u00e1rtida)\n* 2010 La Mari (Chambao) on Ni\u00f1o Raro \u201cTreinta y Tres\u201d album\n* 2009 OBK \"Tal Vez\" [Antipop Version]\n* 2009 Zahara on Lucas \"Palo Al Agua\" album (EMI Espa\u00f1a)\n* 2005 Danny Reus & The Gospel Factory on Lonely Joe \u201cSongs From The Low Side\u201d album (Subterfuge Records)\n* 2002-4 Carita Boronska, advertising campaigns\n* 2001 Naymi, debut album (Sony Music Media)\n* 2001 Carles Benavent on Jos\u00e9 Ortega \"La Rosa De Tu Piel\" album\n\n==See also==\n* [[Superbrands]]\n* [[:es:Rock espanol|Rock Espa\u00f1ol]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.antipop.es Antonio Escobar}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100823104243/http://www.maydrim.com/ Maydr\u00efm Maydrim Official Site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Escobar Nunez, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pamplona]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Madrid]]\n[[Category:Andalusian musicians]]\n[[Category:Rock en Espa\u00f1ol musicians]]\n[[Category:Spanish composers]]\n[[Category:Spanish male composers]]\n[[Category:Spanish film score composers]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:People of Andalusian descent]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax, Removing ELs in text (linkspam) perWP:EL", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antonio_Escobar_N%C3%BA%C3%B1ez"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tanzania", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Tanzania}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tanzania\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tanzania]]\n| first_case      = [[Arusha]]\n| arrival_date    = 16 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=16|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 48\n| deaths          = 10\n| confirmed_cases = 299<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/tanzania/|title=Total Coronavirus Cases in Tanzania|date=2020-04-15 |work=World Dometers}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = https://www.moh.go.tz/en\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Tanzania]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n== Background ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Tanzania medical cases chart}}\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n===Timeline - week 1===\nOn 16 March, the first case in Tanzania was confirmed in [[Arusha]].<ref name=\"WOMC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus Update (Live) - Worldometer |website=www.worldometers.info}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/somalia-tanzania-confirm-first-coronavirus-cases/1767971|title=Somalia, Tanzania confirm first coronavirus cases|date=16 March 2020|work=[[Anadolu Agency]]|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was a 46-year-old Tanzanian who had come to Arusha from [[Belgium]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewhumanitarian.org/news/2020/03/24/coronavirus-tanzania-africa|title=When coronavirus came to Tanzania|date=2020-03-25|website=The New Humanitarian|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the Prime Minister announced a range of measures, including closing schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5494476-agwmfd/index.html|title=Tanzania bans all public gathering, closes schools, suspends the Premier League over Coronavirus|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, two other cases in Tanzania were reported.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Coronavirus-cases-rise-to-three-in-Tanzania/1840340-5495190-view-asAMP-5h7qyyz/index.html?__twitter_impression=true |title=Coronavirus cases rise to three in Tanzania |work=The Citizen |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March two new cases were reported, bringing the total to six. Five cases were located in capital city of [[Dar es Salaam]] with the other in [[Zanzibar]].<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://www.the-star.co.ke/amp/news/africa/2020-03-19-covid-19-tanzania-traces-112-contacts-as-cases-rise-to-six/ |title=COVID-19: Tanzania traces 112 contacts as cases rise to six |last=Vidija |first=Patrick |work=The Star |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, it was announced that cases had risen to 12.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5500244-audo6y/index.html|title=Covid-19 cases in Tanzania now rise to 12, says President|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline - week 2 ===\nOn 23 March, the Government announced that all incoming travelers from COVID affected countries would be placed in quarantine at their own cost for 14 days.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.africanews.com/2020/03/24/coronavirus-tanzania-travel-advisory-no1-of-23032020-update-on-covid-19-in-tanzania//|title=23.03.2020 - Update on COVID-19 in Tanzania|date=23 March 2020|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, it was announced that Zanzibar recorded its second case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Zanzibar-confirms-second-covid-19-case/1840340-5504100-mguw8h/index.html|title=Zanzibar confirms second covid-19 case|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, the first COVID recovery was announced, of the first Arusha patient.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/scienceandhealth/Tanzania-first-Covid19-patient-recovers-cases-rise-to-13/3073694-5504888-xx2sh8/index.html|title=Tanzania first Covid-19 patient recovers|website=The East African|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a third case was recorded in Zanzibar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Zanzibar-health-minister-confirms-third-covid-19-case/1840340-5507362-posb59/index.html|title=Zanzibar health minister confirms third covid-19 case|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline - week 3 ===\nOn 30 March, there were 5 more recorded cases, including 2 in Zanzibar and 3 in mainland Tanzania, bringing the cumulative total to 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/-Covid-19-cases-in-Tanzania-rise-to-19-as/1840340-5508970-fxdgqtz/index.html|title=VIDEO: Covid-19 cases in Tanzania rise to 19 as five more cases|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, the first COVID death was recorded, in Dar es Salaam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Tanzania-records-first-Covid-19-death/1840340-5509582-e6v2lk/index.html|title=Tanzania records first Covid-19 death|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, 1 new case and 1 recovery in Dar es Salaam was announced, bringing the cumulative totals to 20 cases, 2 recoveries and 1 death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/ea/Second-Tanzanian-patient-recovers-from-coronavirus/4552908-5511248-pwab0vz/index.html|title=Second Tanzanian patient recovers from coronavirus|website=The East African|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, a  third recovery in Kagera was announced, bringing the active case number to 16.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailynews.co.tz/news/2020-04-035e876b2d54ef3.aspx|title=COVID-19 Response: US gives 2.3bn/-, patient recovers|last=Ltd|first=Tanzania Standard Newspapers|website=dailynews.co.tz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline - week 4 ===\nOn 5 April, 2 new cases were reported in Zanzibar.\n\nOn 6 April, a  further 2 new cases were reported in Dar es Salaam and Mwanza, bringing the cumulative total to 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/ea/Tanzania-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-24/4552908-5516746-sj18umz/index.html|title=Tanzania's coronavirus cases rise to 24|website=The East African|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, 2 more cases recovered, bringing total recoveries to 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/ea/Tanzania-records-two-more-Covid19-recoveries-infection-slows/4552908-5517192-s01heez/index.html|title=Tanzania records two more Covid-19 recoveries|website=The East African|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, 1 new case was recorded.\n\nOn 10 April, it was announced that there were 5 new cases on mainland, 2 new cases on Zanzibar, and 2 deaths on the mainland, bringing the cumulative case count to 32, and cumulative deaths to 3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/-Tanzania-records-two-more-deaths-as-Covid-19-cases-rise-to-32/1840340-5520214-4vrxe7/index.html|title=Tanzania records two more deaths as Covid-19 cases rise to 32|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline - week 5 ===\nOn 13 April, it was announced that there were 14 new cases on mainland, and 3 new cases in Zanzibar.  In addition, 2 recoveries in Zanzibar were announced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Tanzania-s-Covid-19-cases-rise-to-46/1840340-5522534-5je710/index.html|title=Tanzania's Covid-19 cases rise to 46|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Zanzibar-cases-of-Covid-19-infection-reach-12/1840340-5522620-qv2heqz/index.html|title=Zanzibar cases of Covid-19 infection reach 12|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, the Prime Minister announced 4 more cases in Dar es Salaam, bringing the cumulative total to 53 cases.  \n\nOn 15 April, Zanzibar health minister Hamad Rashid Mohammed, reported 6 more cases, 2 recoveries and its first death. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5524594-avolq3/index.html|title=Zanzibar records first death as cases of Covid-19 infection reach 18|work=The Citizen|date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>  On the same day, 29 new cases on mainland were recorded.  This brought the cumulative total for Tanzania to 88, with cumulative recoveries of 11 and cumulative deaths of 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Tanzania-Covid-19-cases-jump-to-88-as-/1840340-5525152-enmr8kz/index.html|title=Tanzania Covid-19 cases jump to 88 as 29 more test positive in two days|work=The Citizen|date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, 6 people tested positive in Zanzibar, bringing the total to 94.<ref>{{cite we|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5525914-avpe00/index.html|title=Six more test positive in Zanzibar as Covid-19 cases reach 24|work=The Citizen|date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, 53 people tested \npositive, 38 in Dar es Salaam, 10 in Zanzibar, 1 in Mwanza, 1 in Pwani, 1 in Lindi and 1 in Kagera, bringing the total to 147 and cumulative death of 5 people. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Covid-19--Tanzania-cases-jump-to-147-after-53-test-positive/1840340-5527284-anwicrz/index.html|title=Covid-19: Tanzania's cases jump to 147 after 53 test positive|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April, 23 new cases were reported in Zanzibar, where 2 people passed away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Covid-19--Two-dead-as-Zanzibar-records-23-more-cases-/1840340-5528546-wwp6tl/index.html|title=Covid-19: Two dead as Zanzibar records 23 more cases|work=The Citizen|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline - week 6 ===\nOn 20 April, a further 87 people were reported to be infected with the virus, including 16 from Zanzibar.  In addition, 3 new deaths on the mainland were reported, bringing cumulative deaths in Tanzania to 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5529838-avs5j4/index.html|title=Covid-19: Tanzania records 84 new cases as death toll reaches 10|work=The Citizen|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22nd, the Prime Minister announces the case count had risen to 284, with 11 recovered and the death toll remaining at 10. <ref>https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5531084-aw8xpp/index.html</ref>\n\nOn April 24th, 37 more patients had recovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/ea/Covid19-tanzania-records-37-new-recoveries/4552908-5533440-15g0pml/index.html|title=Covid-19: Tanzania records 37 new recoveries|work=The East African|date=April 24, 2020}}</ref> While 15 more were infected with the disease in Zanzibar.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tanzania| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in Tanzania|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Tanzania]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Tanzania]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Tanzania}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tanzania\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tanzania]]\n| first_case      = [[Arusha]]\n| arrival_date    = 16 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=16|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 48\n| deaths          = 10\n| confirmed_cases = 299<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/tanzania/|title=Total Coronavirus Cases in Tanzania|date=2020-04-15 |work=World Dometers}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = https://www.moh.go.tz/en\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Tanzania]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n== Background ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Tanzania medical cases chart}}\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n===Timeline - week 1===\nOn 16 March, the first case in Tanzania was confirmed in [[Arusha]].<ref name=\"WOMC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus Update (Live) - Worldometer |website=www.worldometers.info}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/somalia-tanzania-confirm-first-coronavirus-cases/1767971|title=Somalia, Tanzania confirm first coronavirus cases|date=16 March 2020|work=[[Anadolu Agency]]|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was a 46-year-old Tanzanian who had come to Arusha from [[Belgium]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewhumanitarian.org/news/2020/03/24/coronavirus-tanzania-africa|title=When coronavirus came to Tanzania|date=2020-03-25|website=The New Humanitarian|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the Prime Minister announced a range of measures, including closing schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5494476-agwmfd/index.html|title=Tanzania bans all public gathering, closes schools, suspends the Premier League over Coronavirus|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, two other cases in Tanzania were reported.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Coronavirus-cases-rise-to-three-in-Tanzania/1840340-5495190-view-asAMP-5h7qyyz/index.html?__twitter_impression=true |title=Coronavirus cases rise to three in Tanzania |work=The Citizen |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March two new cases were reported, bringing the total to six. Five cases were located in capital city of [[Dar es Salaam]] with the other in [[Zanzibar]].<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://www.the-star.co.ke/amp/news/africa/2020-03-19-covid-19-tanzania-traces-112-contacts-as-cases-rise-to-six/ |title=COVID-19: Tanzania traces 112 contacts as cases rise to six |last=Vidija |first=Patrick |work=The Star |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, it was announced that cases had risen to 12.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5500244-audo6y/index.html|title=Covid-19 cases in Tanzania now rise to 12, says President|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline - week 2 ===\nOn 23 March, the Government announced that all incoming travelers from COVID affected countries would be placed in quarantine at their own cost for 14 days.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.africanews.com/2020/03/24/coronavirus-tanzania-travel-advisory-no1-of-23032020-update-on-covid-19-in-tanzania//|title=23.03.2020 - Update on COVID-19 in Tanzania|date=23 March 2020|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, it was announced that Zanzibar recorded its second case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Zanzibar-confirms-second-covid-19-case/1840340-5504100-mguw8h/index.html|title=Zanzibar confirms second covid-19 case|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, the first COVID recovery was announced, of the first Arusha patient.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/scienceandhealth/Tanzania-first-Covid19-patient-recovers-cases-rise-to-13/3073694-5504888-xx2sh8/index.html|title=Tanzania first Covid-19 patient recovers|website=The East African|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a third case was recorded in Zanzibar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Zanzibar-health-minister-confirms-third-covid-19-case/1840340-5507362-posb59/index.html|title=Zanzibar health minister confirms third covid-19 case|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline - week 3 ===\nOn 30 March, there were 5 more recorded cases, including 2 in Zanzibar and 3 in mainland Tanzania, bringing the cumulative total to 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/-Covid-19-cases-in-Tanzania-rise-to-19-as/1840340-5508970-fxdgqtz/index.html|title=VIDEO: Covid-19 cases in Tanzania rise to 19 as five more cases|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, the first COVID death was recorded, in Dar es Salaam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Tanzania-records-first-Covid-19-death/1840340-5509582-e6v2lk/index.html|title=Tanzania records first Covid-19 death|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, 1 new case and 1 recovery in Dar es Salaam was announced, bringing the cumulative totals to 20 cases, 2 recoveries and 1 death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/ea/Second-Tanzanian-patient-recovers-from-coronavirus/4552908-5511248-pwab0vz/index.html|title=Second Tanzanian patient recovers from coronavirus|website=The East African|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, a  third recovery in Kagera was announced, bringing the active case number to 16.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailynews.co.tz/news/2020-04-035e876b2d54ef3.aspx|title=COVID-19 Response: US gives 2.3bn/-, patient recovers|last=Ltd|first=Tanzania Standard Newspapers|website=dailynews.co.tz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline - week 4 ===\nOn 5 April, 2 new cases were reported in Zanzibar.\n\nOn 6 April, a  further 2 new cases were reported in Dar es Salaam and Mwanza, bringing the cumulative total to 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/ea/Tanzania-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-24/4552908-5516746-sj18umz/index.html|title=Tanzania's coronavirus cases rise to 24|website=The East African|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, 2 more cases recovered, bringing total recoveries to 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/ea/Tanzania-records-two-more-Covid19-recoveries-infection-slows/4552908-5517192-s01heez/index.html|title=Tanzania records two more Covid-19 recoveries|website=The East African|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, 1 new case was recorded.\n\nOn 10 April, it was announced that there were 5 new cases on mainland, 2 new cases on Zanzibar, and 2 deaths on the mainland, bringing the cumulative case count to 32, and cumulative deaths to 3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/-Tanzania-records-two-more-deaths-as-Covid-19-cases-rise-to-32/1840340-5520214-4vrxe7/index.html|title=Tanzania records two more deaths as Covid-19 cases rise to 32|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline - week 5 ===\nOn 13 April, it was announced that there were 14 new cases on mainland, and 3 new cases in Zanzibar.  In addition, 2 recoveries in Zanzibar were announced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Tanzania-s-Covid-19-cases-rise-to-46/1840340-5522534-5je710/index.html|title=Tanzania's Covid-19 cases rise to 46|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Zanzibar-cases-of-Covid-19-infection-reach-12/1840340-5522620-qv2heqz/index.html|title=Zanzibar cases of Covid-19 infection reach 12|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, the Prime Minister announced 4 more cases in Dar es Salaam, bringing the cumulative total to 53 cases.  \n\nOn 15 April, Zanzibar health minister Hamad Rashid Mohammed, reported 6 more cases, 2 recoveries and its first death. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5524594-avolq3/index.html|title=Zanzibar records first death as cases of Covid-19 infection reach 18|work=The Citizen|date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>  On the same day, 29 new cases on mainland were recorded.  This brought the cumulative total for Tanzania to 88, with cumulative recoveries of 11 and cumulative deaths of 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Tanzania-Covid-19-cases-jump-to-88-as-/1840340-5525152-enmr8kz/index.html|title=Tanzania Covid-19 cases jump to 88 as 29 more test positive in two days|work=The Citizen|date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, 6 people tested positive in Zanzibar, bringing the total to 94.<ref>{{cite we|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5525914-avpe00/index.html|title=Six more test positive in Zanzibar as Covid-19 cases reach 24|work=The Citizen|date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, 53 people tested \npositive, 38 in Dar es Salaam, 10 in Zanzibar, 1 in Mwanza, 1 in Pwani, 1 in Lindi and 1 in Kagera, bringing the total to 147 and cumulative death of 5 people. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Covid-19--Tanzania-cases-jump-to-147-after-53-test-positive/1840340-5527284-anwicrz/index.html|title=Covid-19: Tanzania's cases jump to 147 after 53 test positive|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April, 23 new cases were reported in Zanzibar, where 2 people passed away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Covid-19--Two-dead-as-Zanzibar-records-23-more-cases-/1840340-5528546-wwp6tl/index.html|title=Covid-19: Two dead as Zanzibar records 23 more cases|work=The Citizen|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline - week 6 ===\nOn 20 April, a further 87 people were reported to be infected with the virus, including 16 from Zanzibar.  In addition, 3 new deaths on the mainland were reported, bringing cumulative deaths in Tanzania to 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5529838-avs5j4/index.html|title=Covid-19: Tanzania records 84 new cases as death toll reaches 10|work=The Citizen|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22nd, the Prime Minister announces the cast count had risen to 284, with 11 recovered and the death toll remaining at 10. <ref>https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5531084-aw8xpp/index.html</ref>\n\nOn April 24th, 37 more patients had recovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/ea/Covid19-tanzania-records-37-new-recoveries/4552908-5533440-15g0pml/index.html|title=Covid-19: Tanzania records 37 new recoveries|work=The East African|date=April 24, 2020}}</ref> While 15 more were infected with the disease in Zanzibar.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tanzania| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in Tanzania|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Tanzania]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Tanzania]]\n", "name_user": "Elcaba", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Tanzania"}
{"title_page": "BSFA Award for Best Artwork", "text_new": "{{Infobox award\n| name           = BSFA Award for Best Artwork\n| current_awards = \n| description    = The best science fiction or fantasy artwork published in the previous calendar year\n| presenter      = British Science Fiction Association\n| country        = UK\n| location       = \n| year           = 1980\n| holder         = Likhain for In the Vanishers\u2019 Palace: Dragon I and II\n| website        = [http://www.bsfa.co.uk/bsfa-awards/ BSFA Awards]\n}}\n\nThe [[BSFA Awards]] are given every year by the [[British Science Fiction Association]]. The '''BSFA Award for Best Artwork''' is open to any single science fictional or fantastic image that first appeared in the previous year. Provided the artwork hasn't been published before it doesn't matter where it appears.\n\nPrior to 1994 the award was present for best artist, rather than artwork. [[Jim Burns]] won eight of the sixteen Best Artist awards. He went on to win four Best Artwork awards.\n\n==Winners==\n\n*1979: [[Jim Burns ]]\n*1980: [[Peter Jones (artist)|Peter Jones]]\n*1981: [[Bruce Pennington]]\n*1982: [[Tim White (artist)|Tim White]]\n*1983: Bruce Pennington \n*1984: [[Jim Burns]]\n*1985: [[Jim Burns]]\n*1986: [[Keith Roberts ]]\n*1987: [[Jim Burns]] \n*1988: [[Alan Lee (illustrator)|Alan Lee]] \n*1989: [[Jim Burns]] \n*1990: [[Ian Miller (illustrator)|Ian Miller]]\n*1991: [[Mark Harrison (artist)|Mark Harrison]]\n*1992: [[Jim Burns]]\n*1993: [[Jim Burns]] - cover for ''Red Dust'' by Paul J. McAuley<ref>Matrix issue 111 (April/May 1994) p21</ref>\n*1994: [[Jim Burns]] - cover for ''Interzone'' 79<ref>Matrix issue 114 (April/May 1995) p3</ref>\n*1995: [[Jim Burns]] \u2013 cover for ''Seasons of Plenty''<ref>Matrix issue 122 (November/December 1996) p7</ref>\n*1996: [[Jim Burns]] \u2013 cover for ''Ancient Shores''<ref>Matrix issue 125 (May/June 1997) p6</ref>\n*1997: [[SMS_(illustrator)|SMS]] \u2013 ''The Black Blood of the Dead'', cover for Interzone #116<ref>Matrix issue 131 (May/June 1998) p3</ref>\n*1998: [[Jim Burns]] \u2013 ''Lord Prestimion'', cover for Interzone #138<ref>Matrix issue 137 (May/June 1999) p11</ref>\n*1999: [[Jim Burns]] \u2013 cover of ''Darwinia''<ref>Matrix issue 144 (July/August 2000) p15</ref>\n*2000: Dominic Harman \u2013 ''Hideaway'', cover for Interzone #157)<ref>Matrix issue 149 (May/June 2001) p17</ref>\n*2001: [[Colin Odell]] \u2013 cover for Omegatropic<ref>Matrix issue 155 (May/June 2002) p20</ref>\n*2002: Dominic Harman \u2013 cover for Interzone #179<ref>Matrix issue 162 (July/August 2003) p4</ref>\n*2003: [[Colin Odell]] \u2013 cover for ''The True Knowledge of Ken MacLeod''<ref>Matrix issue 167 (May/June 2004) p4</ref>\n*2004: [[Stephan Martini\u00e8re]] \u2013 cover for Newton's Wake (US edition) \n*2005: [[Pawel Lewandowski]] \u2013 cover for Interzone #200<ref>Matrix issue 179 (June/July 2006) p5</ref>\n*2006: Christopher \"[[Fangorn]]\" Baker \u2013 'Angelbot', cover for Time Pieces<ref>Matrix issue 184 (2007) p5</ref>\n*2007: [[Andy Bigwood]] \u2013 'Cracked World', cover for disLocations\n*2008: Andy Bigwood \u2013 cover for Subterfuge\n*2009: Stephan Martini\u00e8re, cover for Desolation Road (US edition)\n*2010: [[Joey Hi-Fi]] \u2013 cover for ''Zoo City''\n*2011: Dominic Harman - Cover of Ian Whates' ''The Noise Revealed'' <ref>http://www.bsfa.co.uk/2011-bsfa-awards-winners/ \"2011 BSFA Awards winners\", accessed on 23 April 2014</ref>\n*2012: Blacksheep - cover of Adam Roberts's ''Jack Glass'' <ref>http://www.bsfa.co.uk/bsfa-awards-announced \"BSFA Award winners announced\", accessed on 23 April 2014</ref>\n*2013: [[Joey Hi-Fi]] \u2013 cover for Tony Ballantyne's ''Dream London'' <ref>http://www.bsfa.co.uk/bsfa-award-winners-announced \"BSFA Award winners announced\", accessed on 23 April 2014</ref>\n*2014: [[Tessa Farmer]] - installation inspired by [[The Wasp Factory]] from [[Iain Banks]]<ref>{{Cite news\n | first1 = Alison\n | last1 = Flood\n | title = British Science Fiction awards honour 3D Wasp Factory\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/apr/07/british-science-fiction-awards-honour-3d-wasp-factory-tessa-farmer\n | work = The Guardian\n | date = 7 April 2015\n | accessdate = 16 September 2015\n}}</ref>\n*2015:\n*2016: [[Sarah Anne Langton]] \u2013 cover for [[Lavie Tidhar]]'s ''Central Station'' <ref>https://bsfa.co.uk/bsfa-awards-2016-winners-announced/ \"BSFA Awards 2016 Winners Announced\", access on 6 July 2019</ref>\n*2017:\n*2018: Likhain - ''In the Vanishers\u2019 Palace: Dragon I and II'' <ref>https://bsfa.co.uk/bsfa-awards-2018-announced/ \"BSFA Awards 2018 Announced\", accessed on 6 July 2019</ref>\n\n==Best Artist/Artwork nominees==\n\n===1979===\n\n*Jim Burns \n*Chris Foss \n*John Harris \n*Peter Lord \n*Tony Roberts \n*Patrick Woodroffe \n\n===1980===\n*Peter Jones \n*Brian Bolland \n*Carlos Ezquerra \n*Peter Goodfellow \n*Chris Moore \n*Tim White \n\n===1981===\n*Bruce Pennington \n*Chris Achilleos \n*Pete Lyon \n*Chris Moore \n*Tim White \n\n===1982===\n*Tim White \n*Peter Goodfellow \n*Peter Jones \n*Bruce Pennington \n\n===1983===\n*Bruce Pennington \n*Peter Jones \n*Ian Miller \n*Tim White \n\n===1984===\n*Jim Burns \n*Peter Jones \n*Ian Miller \n*Bruce Pennington \n*Tim White \n\n===1985===\n*Jim Burns \n*Peter Jones \n*Rodney Matthews \n*Ian Miller \n*Tim White\n\n...\n\n===2010===\n*Andy Bigwood \u2013 cover for ''Conflicts' (Newcon Press)\n*Charlie Harbour \u2013 cover for ''Fun With Rainbows'' by Gareth Owens (Immersion Press)\n*Dominic Harman \u2013 cover for ''The Cat's Cradle'' by Kurt Vonnegut (Gollancz)\n*Joey Hi-Fi -cover for ''Zoo City'' by Lauren Beukes (Angry Robot)\n*Ben Greene \u2013 ''A Deafened Plea for Peace'', cover for Crossed Genres 21\n*Adam Tredowski \u2013 cover for ''Finch'' by [[Jeff VanderMeer]] (Corvus)\n\n===2011===\n*Dominic Harman - Cover of Ian Whates' ''The Noise Revealed'' (Solaris)\n*Jim Kay - Cover and illustrations of Patrick Ness' ''A Monster Calls'' (Walker)\n*Pedro Marques - Cover of Lavie Tidhar's ''Osama'' (PS Publishing)\n*Anne Sudworth - Cover of Liz Williams' ''A Glass of Shadow'' (Newcon Press)\n\n===2012===\n*Ben Baldwin - cover of ''Dark Currents'' (Newcon Press)\n*Blacksheep - cover of Adam Roberts' ''Jack Glass'' (Gollancz)\n*Dominic Harman - cover of Eric Brown's ''Helix Wars'' (Rebellion)\n*Joey Hi-Fi - cover of Simon Morden's ''Thy Kingdom Come'' (Jurassic London)\n*Si Scott - cover artwork for Chris Beckett's ''Dark Eden'' (Corvus)\n\n===2013===\n*Joey Hi-Fi - Cover for Tony Ballantyne's ''Dream London'' (Solaris)\n*Kevin Tong - Poster for ''Metropolis'' (tragicsunshine.com)\n*Richard Wagner - ''The Angel at the Heart of the Rain'' (Interzone #246)\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bsfa.co.uk/bsfa-awards/ Official website]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:BSFA Awards|Artwork]]<!--other cats in this cat-->\n[[Category:Awards established in 1979]]\n[[Category:1979 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Book art awards]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox award\n| name           = BSFA Award for Best Artwork\n| current_awards = \n| description    = The best science fiction or fantasy artwork published in the previous calendar year\n| presenter      = British Science Fiction Association\n| country        = UK\n| location       = \n| year           = 1980\n| holder         = Likhain for In the Vanishers\u2019 Palace: Dragon I and II\n| website        = [http://www.bsfa.co.uk/bsfa-awards/ BSFA Awards]\n}}\n\nThe [[BSFA Awards]] are given every year by the [[British Science Fiction Association]]. The '''BSFA Award for Best Artwork''' is open to any single science fictional or fantastic image that first appeared in the previous year. Provided the artwork hasn't been published before it doesn't matter where it appears.\n\nPrior to 1994 the award was present for best artist, rather than artwork. [[Jim Burns]] won eight of the sixteen Best Artist awards. He went on to win four Best Artwork awards.\n\n==Winners==\n\n*1979: [[Jim Burns ]]\n*1980: [[Peter Jones (artist)|Peter Jones]]\n*1981: [[Bruce Pennington]]\n*1982: [[Tim White (artist)|Tim White]]\n*1983: Bruce Pennington \n*1984: [[Jim Burns]]\n*1985: [[Jim Burns]]\n*1986: [[Keith Roberts ]]\n*1987: [[Jim Burns]] \n*1988: [[Alan Lee (illustrator)|Alan Lee]] \n*1989: [[Jim Burns]] \n*1990: [[Ian Miller (illustrator)|Ian Miller]]\n*1991: [[Mark Harrison (artist)|Mark Harrison]]\n*1992: [[Jim Burns]]\n*1993: [[Jim Burns]] - cover for ''Red Dust'' by Paul J. McAuley<ref>Matrix issue 111 (April/May 1994) p21</ref>\n*1994: [[Jim Burns]] - cover for ''Interzone'' 79<ref>Matrix issue 114 (April/May 1995) p3</ref>\n*1995: [[Jim Burns]] \u2013 cover for ''Seasons of Plenty''<ref>Matrix issue 122 (November/December 1996) p7</ref>\n*1996: [[Jim Burns]] \u2013 cover for ''Ancient Shores''<ref>Matrix issue 125 (May/June 1997) p6</ref>\n*1997: [[SMS_(illustrator)|SMS]] \u2013 ''The Black Blood of the Dead'', cover for Interzone #116<ref>Matrix issue 131 (May/June 1998) p3</ref>\n*1998: [[Jim Burns]] \u2013 ''Lord Prestimion'', cover for Interzone #138<ref>Matrix issue 137 (May/June 1999) p11</ref>\n*1999: [[Jim Burns]] \u2013 cover of ''Darwinia''<ref>Matrix issue 144 (July/August 2000) p15</ref>\n*2000: Dominic Harman \u2013 ''Hideaway'', cover for Interzone #157)<ref>Matrix issue 149 (May/June 2001) p17</ref>\n*2001: [[Colin Odell]] \u2013 cover for Omegatropic<ref>Matrix issue 155 (May/June 2002) p20</ref>\n*2002: Dominic Harman \u2013 cover for Interzone #179<ref>Matrix issue 162 (July/August 2003) p4</ref>\n*2003: [[Colin Odell]] \u2013 cover for ''The True Knowledge of Ken MacLeod''<ref>Matrix issue 167 (May/June 2004) p4</ref>\n*2004: [[Stephan Martini\u00e8re]] \u2013 cover for Newton's Wake (US edition) \n*2005: [[Pawel Lewandowski]] \u2013 cover for Interzone #200<ref>Matrix issue 179 (June/July 2006) p5</ref>\n*2006: Christopher \"[[Fangorn]]\" Baker \u2013 'Angelbot', cover for Time Pieces\